### Async/Await in C#

Async/await enables asynchronous programming, allowing non-blocking operations while maintaining readable code.

### Basic Async Method

```csharp
public async Task<string> DownloadDataAsync(string url)
{
    using HttpClient client = new HttpClient();
    string result = await client.GetStringAsync(url);
    return result;
}

// Calling
string data = await DownloadDataAsync("https://example.com");
```

### Async Method Patterns

```csharp
// Async void - only for event handlers
public async void Button_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    await LoadDataAsync();
}

// Async Task - no return value
public async Task SaveDataAsync(string data)
{
    await File.WriteAllTextAsync("data.txt", data);
}

// Async Task<T> - returns value
public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
{
    return await CountItemsAsync();
}
```

### Async Naming Convention

Async methods should end with `Async` suffix:

```csharp
Task<string> ReadFileAsync()
Task SaveDataAsync()
Task<int> CalculateAsync()
```

### Await Rules

| Rule | Description |
|------|-------------|
| `await` can only be used in `async` methods | Compiler requirement |
| `await` awaits an awaitable (Task, Task<T>, ValueTask) | Awaitable types |
| `await` suspends execution, not the thread | No blocking |
| Multiple `await` in sequence are serial | Each completes before next |

### Multiple Async Operations

```csharp
// Sequential execution
var result1 = await Task1Async();
var result2 = await Task2Async();  // Starts after Task1 completes

// Parallel execution
var task1 = Task1Async();
var task2 = Task2Async();
await Task.WhenAll(task1, task2);  // Both running concurrently

// Get results
var result1 = await task1;
var result2 = await task2;
```

### Async Streams (C# 8+)

```csharp
await foreach (var item in GetDataAsync())
{
    Console.WriteLine(item);
}

public async IAsyncEnumerable<int> GetDataAsync()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++)
    {
        await Task.Delay(100);
        yield return i;
    }
}
```

### Error Handling

```csharp
try
{
    await someAsyncMethod();
}
catch (HttpRequestException ex)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Network error: {ex.Message}");
}
```

### ConfigureAwait

```csharp
await someTask.ConfigureAwait(false);  // Don't capture synchronization context
```

> **Key Point:** Use `async Task` (not `async void`) for async methods. `await` yields control to the caller until the operation completes. Use `Task.WhenAll` for parallel operations. Async methods should end with `Async` suffix. Avoid mixing blocking calls (.Result, .Wait()) with async code.

### Common Async Methods

```csharp
await Task.Delay(1000);           // Non-blocking delay
await File.ReadAllTextAsync(path); // Async file read
await client.GetStringAsync(url);  // Async HTTP request
await db.QueryAsync(sql);          // Async database (Dapper)
```

### ValueTask for Performance

```csharp
public ValueTask<int> GetCachedAsync()
{
    if (cache is not null)
        return new ValueTask<int>(cache);
    return new ValueTask<int>(LoadAsync());
}

codeExample:
using System;
using System.Net.Http;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

class Program
{
    static async Task Main()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Downloading...");

        string content = await DownloadAsync();
        Console.WriteLine($"Downloaded: {content.Length} characters");

        Console.WriteLine("Done!");
    }

    static async Task<string> DownloadAsync()
    {
        using HttpClient client = new HttpClient();
        return await client.GetStringAsync("https://example.com");
    }
}
